## 3. The Three Layers of Memory

### Layer 1 — Working Memory (Today Only)

This is the trader's mental notepad for the current session. Resets at market close every day because yesterday's intraday context is mostly irrelevant today.

**What it stores:**
- The market regime at each cycle throughout the day — was 9:30 trending? Was 11:00 choppy? Claude sees the regime evolving, not just a snapshot.
- Every setup detected today, whether approved or rejected, and why.
- Every trade placed today — entry price, current status, unrealized P&L.
- Which symbols have been "hot" today (repeated signals in same direction) vs "noisy" (signals flipping).
- The intraday narrative — a running plain-English summary of what the market has been doing.

**What this gives Claude:**
When BTC triggers a mean reversion signal at 2:30 PM, Claude can see that this exact setup triggered at 10:00 AM and 12:00 PM today — and both times the bounce failed within 30 minutes. That context changes everything. Claude should be much more skeptical of a third attempt.

Conversely, if SPY has been in a clean uptrend all day with two successful pullback entries, the third pullback is higher confidence, not lower. Claude can see that pattern.

---

### Layer 2 — Strategic Memory (Persistent, Never Resets)

This is the trader's experience — everything learned over months of watching these specific assets.

**What it stores:**
- Setup performance statistics by setup type, symbol, time of day, and market regime. Not just win/loss — the full distribution. Average win size, average loss size, maximum consecutive losses.
- Regime-to-setup correlation — which setups work in which regimes, derived from actual live results.
- Symbol-specific behavior — does BTC mean reversion at RSI 32 reliably work? Or does it tend to continue down to RSI 25 first? The system learns this from its own trade history.
- Claude's own veto patterns — what reasons does Claude most often cite for rejecting a setup? If Claude rejects 80% of mean reversion setups citing "MACD still negative," that is important signal.
- Weekly patterns — does this system perform better on certain days? The system learns from its own data.

---

### Layer 3 — Market Knowledge Base (Semi-Permanent)

Factual context that enriches Claude's understanding without needing to be derived from trade history.

**What it stores:**
- Known correlation relationships — when VIX spikes above 20, BTC and SPY correlation increases.
- Economic calendar — FOMC dates, CPI releases, NFP dates. The system knows to suppress certain setups in the 2-hour window before major releases.
- Asset-specific structural knowledge — BTC halving cycles, ETH gas fee impact on volatility, SPY options expiration patterns.
- Regime transition history — how long do regimes typically last? A ranging regime running for 3 hours is more likely to break out than one that started 20 minutes ago.

