## 12. The Validation Framework

### Paper Trading Criteria

All of the following must be true for 30 consecutive days before going live:

| Metric | Required Threshold |
|---|---|
| Win rate | Above 52% |
| Expectancy | Positive (avg win × win rate > avg loss × loss rate) |
| Max drawdown | Below 8% of starting capital |
| Sharpe ratio | Above 0.8 on daily returns |
| Max single day loss | Never exceeding 3% |
| Claude calibration score | Above 0.60 |

If any criterion fails: diagnose, do not go live. Strategic memory provides the data to diagnose exactly which setup, which regime, which time of day is failing.

### Live Trading — First 30 Days

Same criteria apply. If any criterion fails in live trading:
- **Step 1:** Auto-reduce to 50% position sizing for 2 weeks
- **Step 2:** If criteria still failing, auto-pause all trading and flag for human review

### The Number That Actually Matters Most

**Expectancy.**

Not win rate — a system can win 80% of the time and still lose money if the 20% losses are huge. Not return — a system can return 10% with a drawdown that would have wiped you out. Expectancy is the average dollar made per dollar risked, over all trades.

```
Expectancy = (Win Rate × Avg Win) - (Loss Rate × Avg Loss)

Example:
Win Rate: 60%, Avg Win: $180
Loss Rate: 40%, Avg Loss: $120

Expectancy = (0.60 × $180) - (0.40 × $120) = $108 - $48 = $60

Meaning: for every trade taken, the system makes $60 on average.
```

If expectancy is positive and you have enough trades to be statistically significant (minimum 50 trades per setup before trusting the number), the system has edge.

